{"sequence":26,"timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:46:01.673996109Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-1-f14e3884","body":"finding_summary: `terminal_status_for_attempt()` no longer answers whether the specific attempt identified by `started_at` reached a terminal state. `run_attempt_boundary_sequence()` always anchors to the latest `run_started`/`run_resumed` for the run id (`src/contexts/project_run_record/queries.rs:33-64`), so once a later resume exists, callers checking an older interrupted attempt (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:943-957`, `src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs:3158-3192`) will incorrectly get `None`. Those repair paths then append a second `run_failed` for the old attempt after the resume boundary, which can poison the live resumed attempt and reintroduce the stale-failure reconciliation bug this bead is meant to eliminate.\nseverity: high\naffected_files:\n- src/contexts/project_run_record/queries.rs:33-83\n- src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:943-957\n- src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs:3158-3192\nremediation_hint: Keep the latest-boundary logic in a helper used only for the current running snapshot, but make `terminal_status_for_attempt()` locate the boundary for the specific `started_at` passed in (the last `run_started`/`run_resumed` at or before that attempt). Add a regression where interrupted-attempt repair runs after a later `run_resumed` and must not append a duplicate terminal event.","dedup_key":"6ce63d9f78c0f1d57ea38ff78a67ae9e73d8f1248d0136cd3e8fdef5d0ed7549","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260414040114","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
